`src/main.rs` is your application entry point. Here's a simple hello world:

```rust
fn main() {
    println!("Hello, world!");
}
```
Save this file, then you can build your project with `cargo build` and run it with `cargo run`.

Build scripts run commands during compilation to generate some Rust source files or other assets. You'd use them when your project depends on something that needs pre-processing, like C bindings. Here's a basic example (without actual C code):

```rust
fn main() {
    println!("cargo:rustc-link-search=native=libdir");
}
```
You define build scripts in the workspace root and Cargo will compile them during build time.
